\c 1  
\cl CHAPTER 1 
\p  
\v 1 And Josiah made \sls (the)\sls* pask \sls (or the Passover)\sls* in Jerusalem to the Lord, and he offered \sls (the)\sls* pask the fourteenth day of the month of the first month, 
\p  
\v 2 ordaining \sls (the)\sls* priests by \em their\em* whiles of days, clothed in stoles, \em or long clothes\em*, in the temple of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 3 And he said to the deacons \add [or to the Levites]\add*, the holy servants of Israel, that they should hallow themselves to the Lord, in \sls (the)\sls* setting of the holy ark of the Lord in the house, that king Solomon, the son of David, builded; 
\p  
\v 4 It shall not be to you \em no more\em* to take it upon \sls (your)\sls* shoulders; and now serveth to our Lord, and do ye \sls (the)\sls* care of that folk of Israel, of the part after towns, and their lineages, 
\p  
\v 5 after \sls (or according to)\sls* the writing of David, king of Israel, and after the great worshipful doing of Solomon, his son, in all the temple, and after your little fathers part of \sls (the)\sls* princehood of them, that stand in the sight of the brethren of the sons of Israel. 
\p  
\v 6 Offer ye \sls (the)\sls* pask, and maketh ready the sacrifices to your brethren; and do ye after the behest of the Lord, that is given to Moses. 
\p  
\v 7 And Josiah gave to the folk that was found \em there\em*, sheep, of lambs, and of kids, and of she-goats, thirty thousand; calves, three thousand. 
\p  
\v 8 These \em gifts\em* be given \sls (out)\sls* of the king’s own things, after the behest \em of the Lord\em* to the people, and to \sls (the)\sls* priests, into \sls (the)\sls* pask; sheep in number two thousand, and calves an hundred. 
\p  
\v 9 And Jeconiah, and Samaeas, and Nathanael, \em his\em* brother, and Sabias, and Ochiel, and Joram, \em gave\em* into \sls (the)\sls* pask, five thousand sheep, and five hundred calves. 
\p  
\v 10 And when these things were nobly done, the priests and deacons \add [or Levites]\add* stood, having therf loaves by lineages. 
\p  
\v 11 And after the parts of the prince-hood of \sls (the)\sls* fathers, they offered to the Lord in the sight of the people, after those things that be written in the book of Moses. 
\p  
\v 12 And they roasted the pask with fire, as it behooved; and they soddened hosts in seething vessels and in pots, with well-willing. 
\p  
\v 13 And they brought \em it\em* to all that there were of the folk; and after these things they made ready to \sls (or for)\sls* themselves and to \sls (or for the)\sls* priests. 
\p  
\v 14 Forsooth the priests offered inner fatness \add [or tallow]\add*, unto the hour was ended; and \sls (the)\sls* deacons prepared to \sls (or for)\sls* themselves \add [or and \+sls (the)\+sls* Levites made ready to themselves]\add*, and to \sls (or for)\sls* their brethren, and to \sls (or)\sls* the sons of Aaron. 
\p  
\v 15 And men sacrificing \add [or the sacri-ficers]\add* offered \em their\em* daughters, after the order and the behests \sls (or commands)\sls* of David; and Asaph, and Zechariah, and Eddinous, that was of the king; 
\p  
\v 16 and the porters by all the gates \em offered\em*, so that none passed his \em gate\em*. Forsooth their brethren prepared to \sls (or made ready for)\sls* them. 
\p  
\v 17 And \em so\em* those things, that pertained to the sacrifice of the Lord, be ended. In that day they did \sls (the)\sls* pask, 
\p  
\v 18 and offered hosts upon the sacrifice of the Lord, after the behest \sls (or the command)\sls* of king Josiah. 
\p  
\v 19 And the sons of Israel, that were found \em present\em*, did in that time \sls (the)\sls* pask, and the feast day of therf loaves by seven days. 
\p  
\v 20 And there was not solemnized such a pask in Israel, from the times of Samuel, the prophet. 
\p  
\v 21 And all the kings of Israel hallowed not such a pask, as did Josiah, and the priests, and deacons \add [or Levites]\add*, and \sls (the)\sls* Jews, and all Israel, that were found in the commemoration, \em or mind-making\em*, \sls (\+em or memory-making\+em*)\sls*, at Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 22 In the eighteenth year, Josiah reigning, \em this\em* pask was hallowed. 
\p  
\v 23 And the works of Josiah be made right in the sight of the Lord, in \sls (or with a)\sls* full dreading heart; 
\p  
\v 24 and those things forsooth that \em were\em* about him be written, in the rather times of them that sinned, and the which were unreligious against the Lord, before, \em or more than\em*, all heathen folk, and the which sinners sought not the words of the Lord upon Israel. 
\p  
\v 25 And after all this deed \sls (or all these deeds)\sls* of Josiah, Pharaoh, king of Egypt, went up, coming to cast away in Carchemish upon Euphrates; and Josiah went into \sls (the)\sls* meeting to \sls (or of)\sls* him. 
\p  
\v 26 And the king of Egypt sent to Josiah, saying, What is to me and to thee, king of Judea? 
\p  
\v 27 I am not sent of \sls (or from)\sls* the Lord \sls (against thee)\sls*, upon Euphrates forsooth is my battle; hastily \em therefore\em* go down. 
\p  
\v 28 And Josiah was not turned again \sls (or did not turn back)\sls* upon the chariot, but he endeavoured himself to over-come Pharaoh \add [or but \+sls (he)\+sls* enforced to overcome him]\add*, not taking heed to the word of the prophet \sls (Jeremiah)\sls*, from the mouth of the Lord; 
\p  
\v 29 but he set to him battle in the field of Megiddo; and \sls (the)\sls* princes came down to \sls (fight)\sls* king Josiah. 
\p  
\v 30 And \em then\em* the king said to his children, \em or \+sls (to his)\+sls* servants\em*, Moveth me away from the battle; forsooth I am greatly made sick \sls (or very weak)\sls*. And anon \sls (or at once)\sls* his children \sls (or his servants)\sls* moved him away from the battle array. 
\p  
\v 31 And he went up upon his secondary chariot; and coming to Jerusalem, he died, and was buried in \em his\em* father’s sepulchre. 
\p  
\v 32 And in all Judah \sls (or in all Jewry)\sls* they bewailed Josiah, and they that before-set with wives, wailed him unto this day; and this is granted to be done evermore in all the kindred of Israel. 
\p  
\v 33 These things forsooth be written in the book of \sls (the)\sls* stories of \sls (the)\sls* kings of Judah, and the glory of Josiah, and his understanding in the law of God, by all \sls (the)\sls* deeds of the doing of him; for evenly those were done of \sls (or by)\sls* him, and the which be not written in the book of \sls (the)\sls* kings of Israel and of Judah. 
\p  
\v 34 And they that were of the kindred took Jehoahaz, the son of Josiah, and set him \sls (as)\sls* king for Josiah, his father, when he was of three and thirty years \sls (old)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 35 And he reigned upon Israel three months; and \em then\em* the king of Egypt put him away, \sls (so)\sls* that he reigned not in Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 36 And he polled \sls (or taxed)\sls* the folk of \sls (or for)\sls* an hundred talents of silver, and of \sls (or for)\sls* a talent of gold. 
\p  
\v 37 And the king of Egypt set Jehoiakim, his brother, king of Judea and of Jerusalem; 
\p  
\v 38 and he bound the master judges of Jehoiakim, and taking Zarius, his brother, he brought him again to \sls (or out of)\sls* Egypt. 
\p  
\v 39 Jehoiakim was of five and twenty years, when he reigned in the land of Judah and of Jerusalem; and he did evil things in the sight of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 40 After this forsooth Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon, went up, and binding Joakim in a strong bond, brought him into Babylon; 
\p  
\v 41 and Nebuchadnezzar took and brought the holy vessels of God, and \sls (made)\sls* sacred \sls (or consecrated)\sls*\em those\em* in his temple in Babylon. 
\p  
\v 42 Forsooth of his uncleanness and unreligiosity it is written in the book of the times of \sls (the)\sls* kings. 
\p  
\v 43 And Joakim, his son, reigned for him; when forsooth he was ordained \em king\em*, he was of eight\sls (een)\sls* years \sls (old)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 44 Forsooth he reigned three months and ten days in Jerusalem; and did evil in \sls (the)\sls* sight of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 45 And after a year Nebuchadnezzar sent \sls (for)\sls*, and brought him over into Babylon, together with the sacred vessels of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 46 And he set Zedekiah king of Judah and of Jerusalem, when he was of one and twenty years \sls (old)\sls*. Forsooth he reigned eleven years; 
\p  
\v 47 and he did evil in \sls (the)\sls* sight of the Lord, and was not adread of the words that be said of Jeremy \sls (or by Jeremiah)\sls*, the prophet, from the mouth of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 48 And he adjured, \em or charged by oath\em*, of \sls (or by)\sls* king Nebuchadnezzar, forsworn went away, and his noll made hard, he over-passed the lawful things of the Lord God of Israel. 
\p  
\v 49 And the dukes of the Lord’s people bare them\sls (selves)\sls* wickedly many things, and they did unpiously over all the wickednesses of \sls (the)\sls* Gentiles; and they defouled \sls (or defiled)\sls* the temple of the Lord, that was holy in Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 50 And \sls (the)\sls* God of their fathers sent by his angel to again-call them, for the which thing he spared to them, and to their tabernacles \add [or their tabernacle]\add*. 
\p  
\v 51 They forsooth scorned in their corners, and that day that the Lord spake, they were bobbing his prophets. 
\p  
\v 52 The which \em Lord\em* is stirred to wrath upon his folk, for their irreligiosity. \em And\em* the kings of \sls (the)\sls* Chaldeans commanded, and went up, 
\p  
\v 53 \sls (and)\sls* they slew the young men of them with \sls (the)\sls* sword, about the holy temple of them; and they spared not to young man, nor to maiden, nor to old man, and to full waxen man \sls (or to fully grown man)\sls*; but also all they be taken into the hands of them; 
\p  
\v 54 and they took all the sacred vessels of the Lord, and the king’s coffers, and brought those into Babylon. 
\p  
\v 55 And they burned up the house of the Lord, and destroyed the walls of Jerusalem, and they burned \sls (up)\sls* his \sls (or its)\sls* towers with fire. 
\p  
\v 56 And they wasted all the worship-ful things, and brought \em them\em* to nought; and they brought \em the people\em* left of \sls (or by)\sls* the sword into Babylon. 
\p  
\v 57 And they were his thralls, unto the time that \sls (the)\sls* Persians reigned, in the fulfilling of the word of the Lord, in the mouth of Jeremy; 
\p  
\v 58 till that the land would do benignly their sabbaths, he sabbatized all the time of their forsaking, in the applying of seventy years. 
\c 2  
\cl CHAPTER 2 
\p  
\v 1 Reigning Cyrus, king of Persia, in the fulfilling of the word of the Lord, in the mouth of Jeremy \sls (or Jeremiah)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 2 the Lord raised up the spirit of Cyrus, king of Persia; and he preached in\sls (to)\sls* all his realm \sls (al)\sls*together by scripture \sls (or by writing)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 3 saying, These things saith Cyrus, king of Persia, The Lord of Israel, the high Lord, hath ordained me king to the world of earths \sls (or over the whole earth)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 4 and he signified to me to build to \sls (or for)\sls* him an house in Jerusalem, that is in Judah. 
\p  
\v 5 If there is any man of your kindred, his Lord go up with him into Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 6 Therefore how many ever dwell in places about, help they them that dwell in that place, in gold and silver, 
\p  
\v 7 in gifts, with horse\sls (s)\sls*, and beasts, and with other things, the which after vows be laid up into the house of the Lord, that is in Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 8 And the standing princes of \sls (the)\sls* lineages of \sls (the)\sls* towns of Judah, of the lineage of Benjamin, and priests and deacons \add [or Levites]\add*, whom the Lord stirred to wend \add [or to go]\add* up, and to build up the house of the Lord, that is in Jerusalem; 
\p  
\v 9 and they, that were in the environ, \em or in \+sls (the)\+sls* compass\em*, of them, should help in \sls (or with)\sls* all silver and gold of it, and in \sls (or with)\sls* beasts, and in \sls (or with)\sls* many vows; \em and\em* many \em others\em*, of whom the wit is stirred, \em help they also\em*. 
\p  
\v 10 And king Cyrus brought forth the sacred vessels of the Lord, the which Nebuchadnezzar translated \sls (or brought over)\sls* from Jerusalem, and \sls (had made)\sls* sacred \sls (or consecrated)\sls* them in his \sls (temple of)\sls* maumet\sls (s)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 11 And Cyrus, king of Persia, bringing them forth, took \em those\em* to Mithradates, that was upon \sls (or over)\sls* the treasures of him. 
\p  
\v 12 Forsooth by him they be taken to Sanabassar, governor of Judea. 
\p  
\v 13 Of these things forsooth this is the number; silvern hallowed vessels of liquors \sls (or for liquids)\sls*, two thousand and four hundred; thirty silvern drink-ing vessels; thirty golden vials \sls (or phials)\sls*; and two thousand and four hundred silvern \em vials \+sls (or phials)\+sls*\em*; and a thousand other vessels. 
\p  
\v 14 Forsooth all the golden and silvern vessels \em were\em* four thousand and four hundred and eight and sixty. 
\p  
\v 15 And they be delivered out to Sanabassar, together with them, that were come into Jerusalem of the captivity, \em or thralldom\em*, of Babylon. 
\p  
\v 16 Forsooth in the time of Artaxerxes, king of Persia, there wrote to him, of these that dwelled in Judea and in Jerusalem, Belemus, and Mithradates, and Tabellius, and Rathymus, Beelteth-mus, and Semellius, the scribe, and others dwelling in Samaria, and in other places, \em they wrote this\em* subject letter to king Artaxerxes. 
\p  
\v 17 Lord, thy children \sls (or thy servants)\sls* Rathymus, and Semellius, the scribe, and other doomsmen of thy court, of things that fall in Celosyria and Phenice \sls (or in Greater Syria and Phoenicia)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 And now be it known to the lord the king, that \sls (the)\sls* Jews, the which went up from you to us, coming into Jerusalem, a city of fleers-away \add [or a city again-flown to]\add*, and a full evil \em city\em*, they build up the ovens of it, and they \sls (re)\sls*set the walls, and rear \sls (or raise up)\sls* the temple. 
\p  
\v 19 That if this city and walls were made up \sls (again)\sls*, \add [or were full ended]\add*, they shall not suffer to yield tributes, but also they shall against-stand to kings. 
\p  
\v 20 And for cause that that thing is done about the temple, to have \em it\em* rightly we have deemed to not despise that same thing, 
\p  
\v 21 but to make known to the lord \add [the]\add* king, that if it shall be seen \em pleasing\em* to the king, be it sought in the books of thy fathers; 
\p  
\v 22 and thou shalt find in \sls (the)\sls* remembrances written of them, and thou shalt know, that that city was again-flown \sls (or rebellious)\sls*, and kings and cities smiting together, 
\p  
\v 23 and \sls (the)\sls* Jews fleeing again \sls (or rebelling)\sls*, and making battles in it always; for the which cause this city was forsaken \add [or is desert\+sls (ed)\+sls*]\add*. 
\p  
\v 24 Now therefore we make known to the lord \add [the]\add* king, that if this city were built up, and the walls of it were areared, there shall be no coming down to thee into Celosyria and Phenice. 
\p  
\v 25 Then the king wrote again to Rathymus, that wrote \em those\em* things that befell, and to Beeltethmus, and to Semellius, the scribe, and to others ordained \em sovereigns\em* and dwelling in Syria, and in Phenice \sls (or in Phoenicia)\sls*, \add [or to others ordained, and dwellers in Syria, and Phenice]\add*, \em he wrote to them\em* these things that be set under. 
\p  
\v 26 I have read the letter, that thou sentest to me. Therefore I commanded \em it\em* to be sought; and it was found, that that city was always withstanding to kings, 
\p  
\v 27 and \sls (the)\sls* men again-fugitive, and making battles in it; and most strong kings have been lordshipping in Jerusalem, and asking tributes of Celosyria and Phenice \sls (or Phoenicia)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 28 Now therefore I \sls (have)\sls* command-\sls (ed)\sls* to prevent those men to build up the city, and to look \add [or to purvey]\add*, that anything be not made hereafter; but that they pass not into full much \add [or go they not forth into more]\add*, 
\p  
\v 29 since they be of malice, so that grievances be not brought there to kings. 
\p  
\v 30 Then after these things were rehearsed \sls (or read)\sls*, that were written of \sls (or from)\sls* Artaxerxes, the king, Rath-ymus, and Semellius, the scribe, and they that were with them ordained, enjoining, hieingly \sls (or hastily)\sls* came into Jerusalem, with horsemen, and people, and with company; and they began to prevent \sls (or to hinder)\sls* the builders. And they voided \sls (or ceased)\sls*\em then\em* from the building of the temple \add [in Jerusalem]\add*, unto the second year of the realm of Darius, king of Persia. 
\c 3  
\cl CHAPTER 3 
\p  
\v 1 King Darius made a great supper to \sls (or for)\sls* all his servants, and to all the master judges of Media and Persia, 
\p  
\v 2 and to all that weared \sls (or wore)\sls* purple, and to governors, and to counsellors, and to prefects under him, from India unto Ethiopia, to an hundred and seven and twenty provinces. 
\p  
\v 3 And when they had eaten and drunken, and were fulfilled, they \sls (re)\sls*turned again \sls (home)\sls*. Then king Darius went up in his little bed-place, and slept, and \sls (then)\sls* was \sls (a)\sls*waked. 
\p  
\v 4 Then those three young men, keepers of the body \sls (or his body-guards)\sls*, the which kept the body of the king \add [or that kept the body of the king]\add*, said one to another, 
\p  
\v 5 Say we each of us a word, that before pass \sls (or surpass)\sls*\em in knowing\em*; and whose ever word seem wiser \em than\em* of another \add [or the tother]\add*, king Darius shall give to him great gifts, 
\p  
\v 6 and to be covered with purple, and to drink in gold, and to sleep upon gold; \em and he shall give him\em* a golden chariot, with the bridle, and a mitre of bis \sls (or fine linen)\sls*, and a bie \sls (or a band)\sls* about the neck; 
\p  
\v 7 and he shall sit in the second place from Darius, for his wisdom; and he shall be called Darius’ cousin. 
\p  
\v 8 Then each \em of them three\em* writing his word, sealed \sls (it)\sls*, and put \em those\em* under the pillow of king Darius; 
\p  
\v 9 and said, When the king hath risen, they will take \add [or they shall give]\add* to him their things written, and whatever thing the king shall deem of \sls (these)\sls* three, and the master judges of Persia, forsooth the word of him is wiser \em than of the others\em*, to him shall be given the victory, as it is written. 
\p  
\v 10 One wrote, Wine is strong. 
\p  
\v 11 Another wrote, The king is stronger. 
\p  
\v 12 The third wrote, Women be strongest; truth overcometh forsooth over all things. 
\p  
\v 13 And when the king had risen up, they took their things written \add [or they took their written things]\add*, and gave \em those\em* to him, and he read \sls (them)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 14 And he sent \sls (forth)\sls* and called all the master judges of Persia, and of \em the land\em*\sls (of)\sls* Media, and the clothed men in purple, and the rulers of \sls (the)\sls* provinces, and \sls (the)\sls* prefects; 
\p  
\v 15 and they set in council, and the writings were read before them. 
\p  
\v 16 And the king said, Calleth the young men, and they shall show their words. And they were called, and they came in. 
\p  
\v 17 And Darius said to them, Show ye to us of these things that be written. And the first, that had said of the strength of wine, he began, 
\p  
\v 18 and said to them, Men! full sur-passing\sls (ly)\sls* strong is wine; to all men that drink it, it beareth down the mind; 
\p  
\v 19 also it maketh the mind vain, both of \sls (the)\sls* king and of the fatherless child; also of servant and of free men, of poor and of rich; 
\p  
\v 20 and it turneth all the mind into secureness, and \add [in]\add* to gladness; and it remembereth not any sorrow and debt; 
\p  
\v 21 and it maketh all the entrails honest \sls (or rich)\sls*; and it remembereth not king, nor master judge; and all things it maketh speak by talent\sls (s)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 22 and when they have drunken, they remember not friendship nor brotherhood, and not long after they take \sls (out)\sls* swords; 
\p  
\v 23 and when they have been drenched of \sls (or drowned in)\sls* wine, and rise, they have no mind \sls (or memory of)\sls* what things they did. 
\p  
\v 24 O men! whether wine is not surpassingly strong, that thus constrain-eth men to do? And this thing said, he held his peace. 
\c 4  
\cl CHAPTER 4 
\p  
\v 1 And the \em next\em* follower began to say, that said of the strength of a king, 
\p  
\v 2 O men! whether men be not sur-passingly strong, the which hold land and sea, and all things that be in them? 
\p  
\v 3 The king forsooth surpasseth above all things, and he hath lordship of them, and they do all thing\sls (s)\sls*, what-ever he will say to them. 
\p  
\v 4 And if he send them to fighters, they go, and destroy hills, and walls, and towers; 
\p  
\v 5 they be slain and slay, and they pass not the word of the king; for if they overcome, they bring to the king all things, whatever things they have spoiled evermore, and all other things. 
\p  
\v 6 And how many ever \sls (or however many)\sls* bear not knighthood, nor fight, but ear \sls (or plow)\sls* the land, again when they shall reap, they bring tributes to the king. 
\p  
\v 7 And he \em is\em*\sls (but)\sls* one \sls (man)\sls* alone; and if he bid to slay, they slay; and if he bid them to forgive, they forgive; 
\p  
\v 8 and if he say \em them\em* to smite \add [or and if he say to smite]\add*, they smite; if he say to outlaw, they outlaw; if he bid \em them\em* to build, they build; 
\p  
\v 9 if he bid to throw down, they throw adown; if he bid to plant, they plant; 
\p  
\v 10 and all \sls (the)\sls* folk and virtues \sls (or hosts)\sls* obeish \sls (or obey)\sls* to him; and over \em all\em* these things he shall sit, and drink, and sleep. 
\p  
\v 11 These forsooth keep him about \add [or in environ keep him]\add*, and may not go each one \sls (or be not able to go each one)\sls*, and do their own works, but in \em his\em* word men obeish \sls (or obey)\sls* to him. 
\p  
\v 12 What manner wise surpasseth not the king before \em others\em*, that thus is loosed? And he held his peace. 
\p  
\v 13 The third, that had said of women, and of truth; this is \em said\em*\sls (or he was called)\sls* Zerubbabel; he began to speak, 
\p  
\v 14 O men! the king is not great, neither many \em other\em* men, nor wine surpasseth before; who is it then that hath lordship of them? 
\p  
\v 15 Whether not women, that have \sls (be)\sls*gotten kings, and all the people, the which \em kings\em* have lordship both of \sls (the)\sls* sea and of \sls (the)\sls* land, and of women they be born? 
\p  
\v 16 And they brought forth them that planted vines, of the which wine is made. 
\p  
\v 17 And they make the stoles, \em or long clothes\em*, of all men, and they do glory to men, and men may not or be not able to be severed from women. 
\p  
\v 18 If they gather together gold and silver, and all fair thing, and see a woman in good\sls (ly)\sls* array, and in good fairness, 
\p  
\v 19 they, forsaking all these things, take heed to her, and the mouth opened, they behold \em her\em*, and they draw more to her than to gold and \add [or]\add* silver, or any precious thing. 
\p  
\v 20 A man shall forsake his father, that nourished him, and his own land, and to a woman he joineth him\sls (self)\sls* together, 
\p  
\v 21 and with a woman he liveth his life, and neither remembereth father, nor mother, nor the land of his birth. 
\p  
\v 22 And therefore it behooveth us to know, that women have lordship of us. Whether ye sorrow not? 
\p  
\v 23 And \em also\em* a man taketh his sword, and goeth in the way to do thefts, and manslaughters, and to sail over the sea, and \em over\em* floods \sls (or on rivers)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 24 and he seeth a lion, and he goeth in darknesses; and when he hath done \em his\em* theft, and guiles, and ravens, he bringeth it to his lief \sls (or to his love)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 25 And again a man loveth his wife more than father or mother; 
\p  
\v 26 and many men be made mad for their wives, and \em many\em* be made thralls for them; 
\p  
\v 27 and many perished, and were strangled, and many have sinned for women, \add [or and sinned, for women]\add*. 
\p  
\v 28 And now \sls (be)\sls*lieveth me; forsooth a king is great, and his power \add [or for great is the king in his power]\add*, for all regions, \em or kingdoms about\em*, be afeared to touch him. 
\p  
\v 29 I saw neverthelater \sls (or neverthe-less)\sls* Apame, the daughter of Bartacus, the wonderful man \add [or the daughter of \+sls (the)\+sls* wonderful man Bartacus]\add*, the secondary wife \sls (or concubine)\sls* of the king, sitting beside the king at the right side; 
\p  
\v 30 and taking away the diadem \sls (or the crown)\sls* from his head, and putting it on herself, and with the palm of her left hand she smote the king. 
\p  
\v 31 And over these things, the mouth opened, he beheld her, and if she laugh to \sls (or at)\sls* him, he laughed, and if she were wroth to him, he glosseth \sls (or he flattereth)\sls*, \em or pleaseth\em*, unto the time that he be reconciled \add [in]\add* to grace. 
\p  
\v 32 O men! why be not women strongest? Great is the earth, and heaven is high, that do these things. 
\p  
\v 33 Then the king and the purpled men beheld either into \sls (the)\sls* other; and he began to speak of truth. 
\p  
\v 34 O men! whether women be not strong? Great is the earth, and heaven is high, and the course of the sun is swift; it is turned in the compass of heaven, and again it runneth again into the same place in a day. 
\p  
\v 35 Whether he is not a great doer, that maketh these things? and truth great, and stronger before all things? 
\p  
\v 36 All \sls (the)\sls* earth calleth inwardly \sls (the)\sls* truth, also it blesseth heaven, and all works be moved and dread it; and there is no wicked thing with it. 
\p  
\v 37 \sls (A)\sls* Wicked king, \em and\em* wicked women, and all the sons \add [or all the works]\add* of men \em be\em* wicked, and there is not truth in them, and in their wickedness they shall perish; 
\p  
\v 38 and truth dwelleth, and waxeth into without end, and it liveth, and wieldeth, into worlds of worlds. 
\p  
\v 39 It is not with truth to out-take \sls (or to accept)\sls* persons, and differences; but it doeth those things that be rightful \add [or rightwise]\add*, to all unrightwise and evil men; and all men be made benign in his works. 
\p  
\v 40 And there is not wickedness in his doom, but \em there is\em* strength, and realm, and power, and majesty of all endurings above time. Blessed be the God of truth! 
\p  
\v 41 And \em then\em* he left \sls (off)\sls* in speaking. And all the peoples cried, and said, Great is truth, and it \sls (sur)\sls*passeth before \em all others\em*. 
\p  
\v 42 Then the king said to him, Ask, if thou wilt, anything moreover, than there be written, and I shall give \sls (it)\sls* to thee, after that thou art found \sls (the)\sls* wiser; and next to me thou shalt sit, and thou shalt be called my cousin. 
\p  
\v 43 Then said he to the king, Be thou mindful of the vow, that thou vowed-est, to build up Jerusalem, in the day in which thou took the realm; 
\p  
\v 44 and to send again \sls (or away)\sls* all the vessels, that be taken from Jerusalem, the which Cyrus parted \sls (or set apart)\sls*, when he slew Babylon, and would send again those things thither. 
\p  
\v 45 And thou wouldest build up the temple, that Idumeans burned \sls (up)\sls*, for Judea is put out of their terms, \em or marches\em*, of \sls (or by)\sls* the Chaldeans. 
\p  
\v 46 And now, lord, this it is that I ask, and that I bid; this is the majesty that I ask of thee, that thou do the vow that thou vowedest to the King of heaven, of \sls (or with)\sls* thy mouth. 
\p  
\v 47 Then Darius, the king, rising kissed him, and wrote epistles to all the dispensators, and prefects, and to men clothed in purple, that they should lead him forth, and them that were with him, all wending \add [or going]\add* up to build Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 48 And to all the prefects that were in \sls (Celo)\sls*Syria and Phenice \sls (or in Greater Syria and Phoenicia)\sls*, and \sls (in)\sls* Lebanon, he wrote epistles, that they should draw \sls (up)\sls* cedar trees from the \em hill\em* Lebanon into Jerusalem, \sls (and)\sls* that they build up the city with them. 
\p  
\v 49 And he wrote to all the Jews, that went up from the realm in\sls (to)\sls* Judea, for freedom, that any man of power, or master judge, and prefect, should not come over to the gates of them, 
\p  
\v 50 and each region, that they had hold \sls (of)\sls*, to be free from them; and that Idumeans leave up \add [or left]\add* the castles of Jews, that they withheld \sls (and that the Edomites should let go of the towns of the Jews, that they held)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 51 and to give year by year twenty talents, into \sls (the)\sls* making of the temple, unto the time that it be full\sls (y)\sls* builded; 
\p  
\v 52 and each day to offer hosts upon the place of sacred things \sls (or the altar)\sls*, as they be commanded; to offer, by all years, \sls (an)\sls*other ten talents; 
\p  
\v 53 and to all men, that go forth from Babylon, to make the city, as freedom were, both to them, and to the sons of them, and to \add [all]\add* the priests that go before. 
\p  
\v 54 Forsooth also he wrote the quantity; and he commanded the sacred stole\sls (s)\sls*, \em or vestment \+sls (s)\+sls*\em*, to be given, in which they should serve; 
\p  
\v 55 and he wrote \sls (the)\sls* wages to be given to the deacons \add [or Levites]\add*, unto the day that the house should be fully ended, and Jerusalem made out; 
\p  
\v 56 and he wrote to all men keeping the city, to give to the builders lots and wages. 
\p  
\v 57 And he left \sls (for)\sls* them \sls (or he let go to them)\sls* all the vessels, that Cyrus had parted \sls (or had set apart)\sls* from Babylon; and all things, whatever Cyrus said, he commanded \em it\em* to be done, and to be sent to Jerusalem. 
\p  
\v 58 And when that young man had gone forth, raising his face toward Jeru-salem, he blessed the King of heaven, 
\p  
\v 59 and said, Of thee, \em Lord\em*, is victory, and of thee is wisdom, and clearness \sls (or glory)\sls*, and I am thy servant. 
\p  
\v 60 Thou art blessed \add [or Blessed thou art]\add*, for thou hast given to me wisdom, and I acknowledge to thee, Lord of our fathers. 
\p  
\v 61 And he took the epistles, \em or \+sls (the)\+sls* letters\em*, and went forth into Babylon; and he came, and told to all his brethren, that were in Babylon. 
\p  
\v 62 And they blessed the God of their fathers, that gave to them forgiveness and refreshing, 
\p  
\v 63 that they should go up, and build Jerusalem, and the temple, where his name is named in it; and they joyed \add [full out]\add* with musics and with gladness \sls (for)\sls* seven days. 
\c 5  
\cl CHAPTER 5 
\p  
\v 1 After these things forsooth there were princes chosen of \sls (or from their)\sls* towns, that they should wend \add [or go]\add* up, by houses, by their lineages, and the wives of them, and the sons and daughters of them, and servants and handmaidens of them, and their beasts. 
\p  
\v 2 And king Darius sent together with them a thousand horsemen, to the time that they brought them into Jerusalem, with peace, and with musics, and timbres, and trumps; 
\p  
\v 3 and all the brethren were playing. And he made them to go up together with them. 
\p  
\v 4 And these be the names of the men, that went up, by their towns, into lineages, and into \sls (the)\sls* part of the princehood of them. 
\p  
\v 5 Priests; the sons of Phinehas, the sons of Aaron, Jesus, \sls (or Jeshua, or Joshua)\sls*, the son of Josedek, the son of Saraeas, \sls (and)\sls* Joakim, the son of Zer-ubbabel, son of Salathiel, of the house of David, of the progeny of Phares \sls (or Perez)\sls*, of the lineage forsooth of Judah, 
\p  
\v 6 that spake under Darius, king of Persia, marvellous doing words, in the second year of his realm \add [or of his reign]\add*, in April \sls (or Nisan)\sls*, the first month. 
\p  
\v 7 Forsooth these it be, that went up of Judah from the captivity, \em or thralldom\em*, of the transmigration, whom Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon, translated \sls (or brought over)\sls* into Babylon; 
\p  
\v 8 and each is \sls (re)\sls*turned again into Jerusalem, and into all the cities of Judea, each into his own city, that came with Zerubbabel, and with Jesus, \sls (or Jeshua, or Joshua)\sls*; Nehemiah, Zar-aeas, and Resaiah, Eneneus, Mardoch-aeus \sls (or Mordecai)\sls*, Beelsarus, Asphar-asus, Reeliah, Romelius, \sls (and)\sls* Baana, one of the princes of them. 
\p  
\v 9 And the number from the Gentiles of them, from the provosts, \em or reeves\em*, of them; the sons of Phoros, two thousand an hundred seventy and two; \sls (the sons of Saphat, four hundred seventy and two)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 10  the sons of Ares, seven hundred fifty and six; 
\p  
\v 11  the sons of Pahath-moab, two thousand eight hundred and twelve; 
\p  
\v 12  the sons of Elam, a thousand two hundred fifty and four; the sons of Zathui, nine hundred forty and five; the sons of Chorbe, seven hundred and five; the sons of Bani, six hundred forty and eight; 
\p  
\v 13  the sons of Bebai, six hundred twenty and three; the sons of Astaa, three thousand two hundred twenty and two; 
\p  
\v 14  the sons of Adonikam, six hundred sixty and seven; the sons of Bagoi, two thousand sixty and six; the sons of Adin, four hundred fifty and four; 
\p  
\v 15  the sons of Ater \sls (the son of)\sls* Hezekiah, ninety and two; the sons of Keilan and Azetas, threescore and seven; the sons of Azurus, four hundred thirty and two; 
\p  
\v 16  the sons of Annias, an hundred and one; the sons of Arom, thirty-two; the sons of Bassa, three hundred twenty and three; the sons of Arsiphurith, an hundred and two \sls (or twelve)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 17  the sons of Baeterus, three thousand and five; the sons of Bethlo-mon, an hundred twenty and three; 
\p  
\v 18  the sons of Netophah, fifty and five; the sons of Anathoth, an hundred fifty and eight; the sons of Bethas-moth, forty and two; 
\p  
\v 19  the sons of Cariathiarius, twenty and five; the sons of Caphira and Beroth, seven hundred forty and three; the sons of Pira, seven hundred; 
\p  
\v 20  the sons of Chadias and Ammidoi, four hundred twenty and two; the sons of Cirama and Gabdes, six hundred twenty and one; 
\p  
\v 21  the sons of Macalon, an hundred twenty and two; the sons of Betolio, fifty and two; the sons of Phinis, an hundred fifty and six; 
\p  
\v 22  the sons of Calamolalus and Onus, seven hundred twenty and five; the sons of Jerechus, two hundred forty and five; 
\p  
\v 23  the sons of Sanaas, three thousand three hundred and thirty. 
\p  
\v 24  Priests: the sons of Jeddu, the son of Jesus, \sls (or Jeshua, or Joshua)\sls*, among the sons of Anasib, nine hundred seventy and two; the sons of Emmer-uth \sls (or Immer)\sls*, a thousand fifty and two; 
\p  
\v 25  the sons of Phassurus, a thousand forty and seven; the sons of Charme, a thousand and seventeen. 
\p  
\v 26 Deacons \add [or Levites]\add*; the sons of Jessue, and Cadmielus, and Bannus, and Sudius, four and seventy; all the number from the two and twenty year, thirty thousand four hundred and two and sixty; sons, and daughters, and wives, all the numbering, sixty thousand two hundred and two and forty. 
\p  
\v 27 The sons of priests, that sung in the temple; the sons of Asaph, an hundred and eight and twenty. 
\p  
\v 28 Ushers forsooth \sls (or The porters)\sls*; the sons of Salum, the sons of Atar, the sons of Tolmon, the sons of Dacubi, the sons of Ateta, the sons of Sabi, \sls (in)\sls* all an hundred and nine and thirty. 
\p  
\v 29 Priests, serving in the temple \sls (or The Temple servants)\sls*; \sls (the)\sls* sons of Esau, the sons of Asipha, the sons of Taboth, the sons of Keras, the sons of Susa, the sons of Phaleas, the sons of Labana, the sons of Aggaba, 
\p  
\v 30 the sons of Acud, the sons of Uta, the sons of Ketab, the sons of Gaba, the sons of Subai, the sons of Anan, the sons of Cathua, the sons of Geddur, 
\p  
\v 31 the sons of Jairus, the sons of Desan, the sons of Noeba, the sons of Chaseba, the sons of Gazera, the sons of Ozius, the sons of Phinoe, the sons of Asara, the sons of Basthae, the sons of Asana, the sons of Maani, the sons of Naphisi, the sons of Acum, the sons of Achipha, the sons of Asur, the sons of Pharakim, the sons of Baaloth, 
